[{"id":32438,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>III</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>II</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mi>IV</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Lyophilic colloids are stable due to charge and solvation, they can be used to protect Lyophobic colloids</p><p>Emulsions are liquid-liquid type of colloids</p><p>If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is added to the excess of hot water, a positively charged sol of hydrated ferric oxide is formed due to adsorption of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> ions. However, when ferric chloride is added to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math> solution, a negatively charged sol is obtained with adsorption of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;ions.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><msub><mi>xH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math><br />Positively charged</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math><br />Negatively charged</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32512,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["emulsification","electrodialysis","peptization","using Tyndall effect"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":32440,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["The refractive indices of the dispersed phase and the dispersion medium differ greatly in magnitude.","The diameter of the dispersed particles is much smaller than the wavelength of the light used.","It is used to distinguish a true solution from a colloidal solution.","During projection of movies in the cinemas hall, Tyndall effect is noticed."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Tyndall effect is observed only when the following two conditions are satisfied.</p><p>(i) The diameter of the dispersed particles is not much smaller than the wavelength of the light used; and</p><p>(ii) The refractive indices of the dispersed phase and the dispersion medium differ greatly in magnitude.</p><p>This is a characteristic property of the colloid solutions.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32441,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Mole of acetic acid absorbed (on 0.6 gram charcoal) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>200</mn><mo>)</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8211;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>200</mn><mo>)</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace></math></p><p>Weight of CH<sub>3</sub>COOH absorbed (on 0.6 gram charcoal)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1200</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gram</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gram</mi></math></p><p>Mass of CH<sub>3</sub>COOH absorbed per gram=<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>grams</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32407,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Adsorption theory of Heterogeneous catalysis involves five steps-<ol>\t<li>Diffusion of reactants to the surface of the catalyst.</li>\t<li>Adsorption of reactant molecules on the surface of the catalyst. (Occurrence of chemical reaction on the catalyst&rsquo;s surface through formation of an intermediate.</li>\t<li>&nbsp;Desorption of reaction products from the catalyst surface&nbsp;</li>\t<li>Making the surface available again for more reaction to occur.</li>\t<li>&nbsp;Diffusion of reaction products away from the catalyst&rsquo;s surface.</li></ol>So, we can deduce from Adsorption theory of catalysis that as the concentration of reactants at active centres increases due to adsorption and thus the rate of the reaction is also increased.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32465,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></math> with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>to</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math> with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>to</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac></math> with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>logn</mi></math> with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Freundlich adsorption isotherm is :</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>kp</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo></math> mass of adsorbate<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo></math> mass of adsorbent<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo></math> eq. pressure</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mi>logp</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>logk</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>mx</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></math></p><p>compairing</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo></math>slope <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>to</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>logK</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mi>logP</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>mx</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math> so slope will be equal to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6867faff-a5c9-4a8d-848c-6450aeff9f69-image.png\" style=\"width: 251px; height: 226px;\" /></p><p>Hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8804;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8804;</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32461,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow><mn>32</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0821</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>300</mn></mrow><mn>1</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8757;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi></math> adsorbs <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gm</mi></math> adsorbs&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32502,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Break an egg carefully and transfer the transparent part of the content to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math> of <math><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math> w/V saline solution and stir well","Keep the egg in boiling water for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> minutes. After removing the shell, transfer the yellow part of the content to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math> of <math><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math> w/V saline solution and homogenize with a mechanical shaker","Keep the egg in boiling water for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math> minutes. After removing the shell, transfer the white part of the content to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math> of <math><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math> w/V saline solution and homogenize with a mechanical shaker","Break an egg carefully and transfer only the yellow part of the content to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math> of <math><mn>5</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math> w/V saline solution and stir well"],"answer":0,"solution":"Preparation of egg albumin sol. is done following two steps.<br /><br />(i) Prepare<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math> of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo></math> solution of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi></math>&nbsp; in water in a&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>250</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi></math> beaker.<br />(ii) Break one egg in a porcelain dish and pipette out the albumin and pour it in sodium chloride solution. Stir well to ensure the preparation of sol.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32504,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Region 3","Region 4","Region 1","Region 2"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The hottest region of the Bunsen flame shown in the figure is the region&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>. The hottest part of the Bunsen flame is present on the one third height from the bottom of the flame.</p><p>The all regions are represented in this figure.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/CVMLSDJJFDASF.jpg\" style=\"width: 236px; height: 166px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":32448,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> added to KI solution","KI added to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> solution","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mi>x</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> in water","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> added to hot water"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> added to hot water,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f871cf71-2160-4f97-887f-fdf0586564c4-ed09eacc-f2af-4159-82b3-d6dcf7194d01-ce117026-f239-4d9f-ab92-f4ead34eb900-image.png\" style=\"width: 247px; height: 70px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></math> When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is added to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KI</mi></math>,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/69844817-e584-4c02-847e-a8648856e519-6c58a644-135b-4f7d-adc5-316564256e7b-5d1f7c1c-f6de-42a6-a0f3-820a4f4ecc20-image.png\" style=\"width: 354px; height: 70px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>)</mo></math> When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Kl</mi></math> is added to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AgNO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>,&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/485c1447-1e80-431b-b9d9-1305979369e2-aef35db5-521b-4c7d-a906-fd6a760fd855-4966b658-fc7d-47e8-a9c4-7f59165b9bd2-image.png\" style=\"width: 383px; height: 69px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>4</mn></mfenced><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math> in water&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>Al</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;positively charged&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32423,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Water vapours are absorbed by anhydrous calcium chloride. There is a&nbsp;decrease&nbsp;in surface energy during adsorption.&nbsp;As the adsorption proceeds, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;H</mi></math> becomes more and more negative.&nbsp;Adsorption is accompanied by decrease&nbsp;in entropy of the system. Thus, option A and C are incorrect.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32473,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["(d) and (a)&nbsp;","(b) and (c)","(a) and (b)","(c) and (d)"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>(a) When gas is adsorbed on metal surface.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> become less negative with progress of reaction because number of active sites decreases.<br />(b) Gas with greater value of critical temperature <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></mfenced></math> absorbed more. As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mfenced><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mfenced><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced></math> So <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> absorbed more than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.</p><p>Statement (c) is wrong because residual forces decrease as adsorption proceeds further.</p><p>Statement (d) is also wrong because temperature opposes extent of adsorption.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32507,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>54</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mg</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>18</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mg</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mg</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>42</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mg</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Milliequivalents&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi>eqs</mi></msub><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mtext>CH</mtext><mn>3</mn></msub><mtext>COOH</mtext></math>&nbsp;(initial)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mtext>0.06</mtext><mo>=</mo><mtext>3</mtext></math><br /><br />Milliequivalents of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mtext>CH</mtext><mn>3</mn></msub><mtext>COOH</mtext></math>&nbsp;(final)<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mtext>0.042</mtext><mo>=</mo><mtext>2.1</mtext></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mtext>CH</mtext><mn>3</mn></msub><mtext>COOH</mtext></math>&nbsp;adsorbed<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mtext>2.1</mtext><mo>=</mo><msub><mtext>0.9 M</mtext><mi>eqs</mi></msub></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>0</mn><mn>-1</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mtext>60 g</mtext><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>0</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>g</mo></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>5</mn> <mn>4</mn> <mn>0</mn> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mn>1</mn> <msup> <mn>0</mn> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> <mn>4</mn> </mrow> </msup> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>0.054 g</mtext> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>mg</mo></math><br /><br />Amount of acetic acid adsorbed per gram of charcoal<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>5</mn><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mtext>18 mg/g</mtext></math>&nbsp;of charcoal.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":32525,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["0","1","2","insufficient data"],"answer":0,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":32455,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The phenomenon of scattering of light by colloidal particles as a result of which the path of the beam becomes visible is called a tyndall effect. Smaller the diameter and similar the magnitude of refractive indices, lesser is the scattering and hence the tyndall effect and viced-versa. The diameter of the dispersed phase particle should not be smaller than the wavelength of light used because they won&#39;t be able to scatter the light so, therefore, the diameter of the dispersed particles should be equal or not much smaller than the wavelength of the light used.<br />2. The refractive indices (i.e. the ratio of the velocity of light in vacuum to the velocity of light in any medium) of the dispersed phase and the dispersion medium should differ greatly in magnitude than only the particles will be able to&nbsp;scatter the light and tyndall effect will be observed. On the other hand, if the refractive indices of the dispersed phase and dispersion medium are almost similar in magnitude, then there will be no scattering of light and hence, therefore, no tyndall&nbsp;effect is observed.<br />Hence answer <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></math> are correct.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32411,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Methanal","Methanoic acid","&nbsp;Ethanol","Methanol"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Methanol can be produced from syn gas (a mixture of carbon monoxide and hydrogen) through a different process, mainly through&nbsp;synthesis reaction.&nbsp;In this process, syn gas is passed over a heterogeneous catalyst,&nbsp;at high temperatures and pressures.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><munder><mrow><mi>CO</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></mrow><mo>&#9183;</mo></munder><mrow><mi>Water</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gas</mi></mrow></munder><munderover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>catalyst</mi><mi>Cobalt</mi></munderover><munder><mrow><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mfenced></mrow><mi>Methanol</mi></munder></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32501,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Adsorption is monolayer","Adsorption increases with increase in temperature","Enthalpy of adsorption is greater than  <math><mn>100</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","Energy of activation is low"],"answer":3,"solution":"In the case of physical adsorption there is almost nil energy of activation and very low enthalpy change.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":32456,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["positive and positive","positive and negative","negative and negative","negative and positive"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CdS</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sol</mi></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>ve</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sol</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>TiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sol</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>ve</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sol</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32483,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["solid is dispersed in gas.","liquid is dispersed in water.","gas is dispersed in solid.","gas is dispersed in liquid."],"answer":0,"solution":"An aerosol is a colloidal solution of solid or liquid particles in the air or other gas, for example smoke, dust etc. are considered as an aerosol.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32492,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><msup><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mi>p</mi></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"According to the Freundlich adsorption isotherm, <math><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>K</mi><msup><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></msup></math><br /><br />Taking log on both sides.<br /><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mi>K</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfrac><mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">log</mi></mrow><mo>⁡</mo><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></mrow></math><br /><br />Slope from graph <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math> or, <math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math><mo>∴</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>K</mi><msup><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow></msup></math><br /><br />or <math><mfrac><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>∝</mo><msup><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow></msup></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32420,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A-I, B-III, C-IV, D-II","A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II","A-III, B-I, C-II, D-IV","A-I, B-III, C-II, D-IV"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>(A) Osmosis: It is a process by which the molecules of a solvent pass from a solution of low concentration to a solution of high concentration through a semi-permeable membrane.</p><p>(B) Reverse osmosis:&nbsp;The direction of osmosis can be reversed if a pressure larger than the osmotic pressure is applied to the solution side. Now the pure solvent flows out of the solution through the semi-permeable membrane. This phenomenon is called reverse osmosis.</p><p>(C) Electroosmosis:&nbsp;When electrophoresis, i.e., movement of particles is prevented by some suitable means, it is observed that the dispersion medium begins to move in an electric field. This phenomenon is termed electroosmosis.</p><p>(D) Electrophoresis:&nbsp;When an electric potential is applied across two platinum electrodes dipping in a colloidal solution, the colloidal particles move towards one or the other electrode. The movement of colloidal particles under an applied electric potential is called electrophoresis.</p><p>So the correct matching is A-III, B-I, C-IV, D-II.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32519,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["$D < A < C < B$","C $ < $ B $ < D < A$","$A < C < B < D$","B $ < D < A < C$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Higher the gold number lesser will be the protective power of colloid.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":32481,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Decrease in <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> and increase in <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","Increase in <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> and decrease in <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","Increase in <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> and increase in <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>","Decrease in <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> and decrease in <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msub><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mn>0.5</mn></math><br />Physical adsorption increases with decrease in Temperature.<br />According to relation <math><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8593;</mo></math> on <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8593;</mo></math><br />So adsorption increases on increasing pressure.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32405,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<p>Film of lyophilic&nbsp;sol is formed over lyophobic sol</p>","<p>Lyophilic sol is dispersed in lyophobic sol</p>","<p>Film&nbsp;of lyophobic&nbsp;sol is formed over lyophilic sol</p>","<p>Lyophobic sol is coagulated</p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"Film of lyophilic sol is formed over lyophobic sol as&nbsp;lyophilic sol acts as a protective colloid.&nbsp;Lyophobic solutions are unstable in nature. When a lyophilic sol is added to lyophobic sol, stability of lyophobic sol increases due to a protective film of lyophilic sol present over the lyophobic sol.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32419,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The graphical representation of logarithmic form of Freundilich adsorption isotherm is as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ec4dfee9-7a5b-4d1f-a095-521e8a642050-9896033.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 288px;\" /></p><p>The logarithmic form of Freundilich adsorption isotherm is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>logk</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mi>logP</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>logk</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6020</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>log</mi><mn>4</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mo>&#183;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32514,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["solid particles dispersed in gas","solid particles dispersed in a liquid","liquid particles dispersed in gas","gaseous particles dispersed in a liquid"],"answer":2,"solution":"Fog has liquid as dispersed phase and gas as dispersion medium.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":32415,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>505</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7033</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>505</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7033</mn></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The expression for the Freundlich isotherm can be represented by the following equation</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Taking log on both sides</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>logk</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mi>logP</mi></math></p><p>On comparing with given equation of straight line, we get</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>505</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>logK</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>505</mn></math></p><p>So, the answer is 3 and 2.505</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":32471,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["(i) &ndash; (b), (ii) &ndash; (c), (iii) &ndash; (e), (iv) &ndash; (d)","(i) &ndash; (d), (ii) &ndash; (b), (iii) &ndash; (a), (iv) &ndash; (e)","(i) &ndash; (e), (ii) &ndash; (c), (iii) &ndash; (a), (iv) &ndash; (f)","(i) &ndash; (d), (ii) &ndash; (b), (iii) &ndash; (e), (iv) &ndash; (f)"],"answer":2,"solution":"<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 100%;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>\t\t\t<p>Dispersed Phase</p>\t\t\t</td>\t\t\t<td>\t\t\t<p>Dispersion medium</p>\t\t\t</td>\t\t\t<td>Type of colloid</td>\t\t\t<td>Examples</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Solid</td>\t\t\t<td>Solid</td>\t\t\t<td>Solid sol</td>\t\t\t<td>Some coloured glasses and gem stones</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Solid</td>\t\t\t<td>Liquid</td>\t\t\t<td>Sol</td>\t\t\t<td>Paints, cell fluids</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Solid</td>\t\t\t<td>Gas</td>\t\t\t<td>Aerosol</td>\t\t\t<td>Smoke, dust</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Liquid</td>\t\t\t<td>Solid</td>\t\t\t<td>Gel</td>\t\t\t<td>Cheese, butter, jellies</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Liquid&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>Liquid</td>\t\t\t<td>Emulsion</td>\t\t\t<td>Milk, hai cream</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Liquid</td>\t\t\t<td>Gas</td>\t\t\t<td>Aerosol</td>\t\t\t<td>Fog, mist cloud, insecticide sprays</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Gas</td>\t\t\t<td>Solid</td>\t\t\t<td>Solid sol</td>\t\t\t<td>Pumice stone, foam rubber</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Gas&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>Liquid</td>\t\t\t<td>Foam</td>\t\t\t<td>Froth, whipped cream, soap lather</td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32467,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["below which the aqueous solution of detergents starts freezing.","below which the formation of micelles takes place.","above which the aqueous solution of detergents starts boiling.","above which the formation of micelles takes place."],"answer":3,"solution":"(i) Micelles formation take place only above a particular temperature called as kraft temperature <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mi>K</mi></msub><mo>)</mo></math> (ii) Concentration above which micelle formation become appreciable is critical micells concentration","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (06 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":32489,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Surface Chemistry","question":"","options":["Combustion of Coal","Hydrogenation of Vegetable oils","Ostwald's process","Haber's process"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> Since Combustion of Coal is a fast and spontaneous process, no catalyst is required.<br /><br /><math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> Catalyst used in&nbsp;Hydrogenation of Vegetable oils is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ni</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo></math><br /><br /><math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> Catalyst used in&nbsp;Haber&#39;s process is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.<br /><br /><math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> Catalyst used in Ostwald&#39;s process is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pt</mi><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null}]